20064.summary:
As an example, assume you have a file containing this JSON document:



    {

        "droids": [

            {

                "name": "C-4PO",

                "class": "protocol"

            },

            {

                "name": "R2-D2"

            }

        ]

    }



And I then ran a task that looked like so over this JSON file:



    - name: Fix issues with droid information

      jsonmod:

        data_str: "{{ item.data }}"

        json_path: "{{ item.path }}"

        path: "/path/to/droids.json"

      with_items:

        - { data: "C-3PO", path: "droids[0]name" }

        - { data: "astromech", path: "droids[1]class" }



That document would now look like this:



    {

        "droids": [

            {

                "name": "C-3PO",

                "class": "protocol"

            },

            {

                "name": "R2-D2",

                "class": "astromech"

            }

        ]

    }



The `jsonmod` module can also add actual JSON:



    - name: Add info about BB-8

      jsonmod:

        data_json: {"name": "BB-8", "class": "astromech"}

        json_path: "droids[2]"

        path: "/path/to/droids.json"



The result would be:



    {

        "droids": [

            {

                "name": "C-3PO",

                "class": "protocol"

            },

            {

                "name": "R2-D2",

                "class": "astromech"

            },

            {

                "name": "BB-8",

                "class": "astromech"

            }

        ]

    }



Finally, it can also remove nodes, like so:



    - name: We don't need class data now

      jsonmod:

        json_path: "droids[{{ item }}]class"

        path: "/path/to/droids.json"

        remove: yes

      with_sequence: start=0 end=2



The result would be:



    {

        "droids": [

            { "name": "C-3PO" },

            { "name": "R2-D2" },

            { "name": "BB-8" }

        ]

    }



My rationale for this is quite similar to what the `lineinfile` module is commonly used for. The difference is that JSON is a serialized format and therefore you can't make assumptions about what the file looks like.

